            "creation_date": 1500971923,
            "body": "<p>Your current approach is very clear and straight forward I'd go with that if I were you. Anyway Regular Expressions are an option:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>(?&lt;=^(?:.{3}|.{4}|.{5})).\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://ideone.com/Kn1yUs\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Java live demo<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 45298086,
            "question_id": 45297910,
            "last_edit_date": 1500972346
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-8Uw3zcKUw5c/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAACE/yaXF1QrLkjM/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
                "account_id": 8733263,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6532640,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6532640/natngs",
                "reputation": 874,
                "display_name": "NatNgs",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1500971976,
            "creation_date": 1500971976,
            "body": "<p>Following the example you give, I will answer something like that:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>// Keeping 3 firsts char; will replace the 3 of the center, and keep all to the end\n^(.{3}).{3}(.*)$\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So in Java:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>str.replaceAll(\"^(.{3}).{3}(.*)$\", \"$1***$2\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 45298107,
            "question_id": 45297910
        },
